Observation Details: While observing what appeared to be a juvenile red-tailed hawk perched in a tree, we noticed it was closely watching a melanistic eastern grey squirrel (who happened to be entirely missing a tail). The tail-less squirrel was strangely fearless, at times seeming to inch closer to the hawk, to which the bird responded by hopping to a closer branch, and, a few times, attempting to snatch up the squirrel. On the fourth or fifth of these attempts, the squirrel ran down the trunk of the tree and across the adjacent cemetery road. As the young hawk attempted to take advantage of this clear shot at the  squirrel, suddenly, a larger, more well-defined (adult) red-tail hawk swooped in from the north, crashing into the younger hawk and continued on its southbound way. After this moment of great birding drama, we were unable to spot the younger hawk in the vicinity, although none of us (a physically-distanced & masked birding party of 3!) saw it fly off. In the end, the squirrel (whose lack of tail may be explained by an earlier occurrence of such behaviours) returned to its original perch on the tree where these events began.
Seen in distance fly above Woodbine Park area - possibly Red Tailed
Solo hawk soaring/circling...exceptionally pale underside with almost no marking, except for dark patagial bars. Most Likely a juvenile red-tail, light-morph
Moving quickly to the north and being mobbed by another bird...possibly a sharp-shinned due to size, but didn't get a clear enough look
Soft wooting heard clearly and recorded
Lone juvenile with fluffy down feathers in nest along east side treeline overlooking the roadway

Observation Details: Waited a week to post this - An incredible delight and a Canadian lifer! Size and patterning unmistakable for a Barred Owl. Observed it hunting in low branches for about 30 minutes. Found it by following a suite of noises from nearby cardinals, white breasted nuthatch, juncos and squirrels presumably disturbed by the owlâ€™s presence. A few poor record photos were taken with my phone through binoculars.

Observation Details: A small warbler, dull yellow-olive overall with slightly stronger yellow on underparts. Noticed a bit more grey on its head as well as a pale eye-line and eye-ring. Also, a distinctively thin, sharp-pointed bill. The bird was foraging on the ground with a group of about five black-cap chickadees and was seemingly as curious and unafraid of my presence as the chickadees. Located on the west end of the trail in the shrubbery that runs into some backyards on Roxborough Drive. I am guessing this is the same continuing individual spotted by others in this area over the past month or so. Once it began to snow a bit, the warbler and it's chickadee pals few back toward the creek area. Took a few poor videos with my phone. Lifer!

Continuing. Last reported Jan 24. Last seen by myself on Jan 21. A small warbler, yellow-olive overall with stronger yellow on underparts. A bit more grey on its head, as well as a pale eye-line and eye-ring. Also, a thin, sharp bill. Its colours really popped as it hopped amongst snowy rocks in the stream a bit west of the bridge underpass. A Song sparrow and a pair of singing winter wrens were also nearby feeding from the stream.

Observation Details: Distinct grey head and throat, yellowish belly and yellow-green back with slight eye ring (not full and distinct to rule out a Connecticut). This warbler was solo and very reclusive, feeding only near the ground and in very low shrubs. Strongly thinking a (very late) migrating female or immature male Mourning Warbler (no sign of adult maleâ€™s black throat patch). I have seen plenty of Nashville Warblers and Common Yellowthroats...the moment I saw this bird and its behavior, I knew it was a first for me!

Still happy to submit one final checklist for the year to account for a single vivid-red male cardinal who witnessed my attempt to stay balanced. Onto 2021!
